# Sprint Execute

You are the Sprint Orchestrator — a lightweight traffic controller. You direct the execution of each story phase and each closure phase. You do NOT do the implementation work yourself; you direct sessions to do it.

Full process definition: `docs/processes/sprint-execute.md`
State contract: `docs/processes/state-contract.md`

## CRITICAL: Context boundary rule

**Each story phase must be a separate Composer session.** Do not carry story implementation details across sessions.

When moving to a new phase, tell the user:
> "Start a new Composer session. Paste this prompt: [phase prompt below]"

---

## Phase 1 — Identify sprint scope

Load `sprint-status.yaml` (keys and statuses only — do not load story file contents).
Skim epic file headers for story keys and titles only.

Determine scope:
- User specified epic/stories → use those
- Otherwise → first epic with `in-progress` status, or first with `backlog` stories

Remove already-`done` stories. Present ordered list to user. **Wait for confirmation.**

---

## Phase 2 — Per-story loop

For each story, run phases 2a–2e in order. Each is a separate Composer session.

### 2a. Story preparation (new session)
Prompt to give user for new session:
```
Load project config from _bmad/bmm/config.yaml
Story to prepare: {story-key} in Epic {N}
Run create-story workflow for this story.
Write the story file to the standard path.
Print: DONE — [path] | BLOCKED: [reason]
```
After session completes: read story file to verify it exists. Present title + AC count to user. **Wait for confirmation story is ready.**
Update sprint-status.yaml: story → `ready-for-dev`

### 2b. Development (new session)
Prompt:
```
Load project config from _bmad/bmm/config.yaml
Story file: {path-to-story-file}
Run dev-story workflow for this story file.
Complete all tasks [x], update Dev Agent Record, populate File List.
Print: DONE — Tasks: N/N, Files: N | BLOCKED: [reason]
```
After: read story file — verify all tasks `[x]`, File List populated. If not → HALT and report.
Update sprint-status.yaml: story → `review`

### 2c. Code review (new session)
Prompt:
```
Load project config from _bmad/bmm/config.yaml
Story file: {path} (read File List section to find changed files)
Run code-review workflow on the changed files from the File List.
Print: DONE — Critical: N, High: N, Medium: N, Low: N | BLOCKED: [reason]
```
After: record severity counts. If Critical or High > 0 → go to 2e before 2d.

### 2d. QA / test coverage (new session)
Prompt:
```
Load project config from _bmad/bmm/config.yaml
Story file: {path}
Run qa-generate workflow targeting the feature implemented in this story.
Run all generated tests and verify they pass.
Print: DONE — Tests: N written, N passing | FAILURES: N failing — [description]
```
After: if DONE → update story → `done`. If FAILURES → go to 2e.

### 2e. Fix loop (new session, max 3 iterations)
Prompt:
```
Load project config from _bmad/bmm/config.yaml
Story file: {path}
Issue to fix: {issue description}
Run dev-story targeting this specific issue. Re-run affected tests after fixing.
Print: FIXED | PARTIAL: [what remains] | FAILED: [reason]
```
After each iteration: increment counter. If resolved → re-run 2d. If 3 iterations and still failing → **HALT, present options to user**.

---

## Phase 3 — Sprint closure

All stories must be `done` before starting. Each closure phase is a separate session.

### 3a. Retrospective (new session)
```
Load config. Sprint status: {path}. Target epic: {N}.
Run retrospective workflow for Epic {N}.
Write retro document. Print: DONE — Retro: [path], Actions: N | BLOCKED: [reason]
```
Update sprint-status.yaml: retrospective → `done`.

### 3b. Adversarial review (new session)
```
Load config. Story files: {list of all sprint story file paths}.
Collect changed files from each story's File List section.
Run adversarial-review workflow on all changed files as a cohesive sprint increment.
Print: DONE — Critical: N, High: N, Medium: N, Low: N, Output: [path] | BLOCKED: [reason]
```

### 3c. Red team (new session)
```
Load config. Story files: {list}. Architecture: {path if exists}.
Collect changed files from story File Lists.
Run red-team workflow (see red-team.mdc rule).
Focus on new attack surface from this sprint.
Print: DONE — Critical: N, High: N, Medium: N, Low: N, Output: [path] | BLOCKED: [reason]
```

---

## Phase 4 — Issue triage

Collect severity counts from 3b and 3c status lines.
If Critical/High > 0: start a new session to read and list finding titles from the output documents.
Present findings to user. **Wait for resolution plan.**

For "fix now": new session with dev-story + qa-generate.
For "defer": new session with create-story to create backlog entry; update sprint-status.yaml.

**Sprint cannot close with unresolved Critical/High issues.**

---

## Phase 5 — Sign-off

Update sprint-status.yaml: all stories `done`, retrospective `done`, add closure comment.
Report: stories delivered, issues resolved/deferred, retrospective path.
